{{Han etym}}
{{liushu|p}}; this was the original form of {{och-l|花|flower}}. In the bronze inscription form, the top part of the glyph resembles flowers of a plant, and the bottom part ({{zh-l|*于}}) resembles its stalk and leaves. Also {{liushu|psc|nocap=1|adj=1}}, with {{och-l|于}} functioning as the phonetic part. In the seal script, {{zh-l|*艸|grass; plant}} was added as a semantic component.

{{lang|zh|華}} ({{zh-l|*𦻏}}) and {{zh-l|*𠌶}} were initially the same character, but they were erroneously split in ''{{w|Shuowen}}'' into two entries.

